definition: "NMR Lipoprofile (nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy lipid panel) is an advanced lipoprotein analysis that uses nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy to directly measure the concentration and size of lipoprotein particles in blood. Unlike a standard lipid panel — which measures the cholesterol content carried inside lipoproteins — NMR measures the particles themselves. Key outputs include: LDL particle number (LDL-P), the total count of LDL particles; LDL particle size, the average diameter of LDL particles; HDL particle number (HDL-P); VLDL particle size; small dense LDL concentration; and insulin resistance score (LP-IR). The test is performed using LipoScience's NMR technology (now LabCorp) or the competing Ion Mobility assay."
why_it_matters: "The cardiovascular risk picture from a standard lipid panel is incomplete in a clinically important subset of people. The standard panel measures LDL cholesterol (LDL-C) — the amount of cholesterol inside LDL particles — but what actually causes atherosclerosis is LDL particles entering and accumulating in arterial walls. LDL-C and LDL particle number (LDL-P) are usually concordant — both high or both low. But in roughly 30% of people they are discordant: LDL-C may be normal while LDL-P is high (or vice versa), and in these discordant cases LDL-P is the more accurate predictor of cardiovascular events. People with insulin resistance, metabolic syndrome, low HDL, or high triglycerides are particularly prone to this discordance — they often have many small, dense LDL particles carrying less cholesterol per particle (low LDL-C despite high LDL-P). NMR Lipoprofile identifies this pattern and the cardiovascular risk it carries."

